the city extends mostly westward and southward from the bay which is entered through a narrow inlet and which divides into three main harbours marimelena guanabacoa and atarés the sluggish  almendares river  traverses the city from south to north entering the  straits of florida  a few miles west of the bay  the low hills on which the city lies rise gently from the deep blue waters of the straits a noteworthy elevation is the 200foot 60metre high limestone ridge that slopes up from the east and culminates in the heights of  la cabaña  and  el morro  the sites of colonial fortifications overlooking the bay another notable rise is the hill to the west that is occupied by the  university of havana  and the princes castle
